<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUSH AND GORBACHEV'S MALTA SUMMIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The well-kept secret of the Bush bombshell dropped at the very first session of 
the historic summit -- that the 20th summer Olympics be held in Berlin -- had 
little connection to the weighty work at hand (Part A, Dec. 3). It was no great 
appetizer for the momentous menu of world alignment lying ahead. It 
demonstrated Bush's unawareness of the sensitivity, both East and West Europe 
have to the German problem. He likes throwing a wild card in the deck, as in 
Danforth (Quayle). 
</P>
<P>
Did Bush try to preempt the usual Gorbachev by a bold announcement of worldwide 
significance? It fell as flat as the Russian ruble, with the thud of silence. 
</P>
<P>
LOUIS E. HYMAN 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
