<P>
LOCAL TEAMS HOPING FOR BIG-TIME DAY; 
</P>
<P>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL: USD AND USIU TRAVEL FOR GAMES WITH RANKED TEAMS, AND SDSU 
PLAYS HOST TO USC FOR THE FIRST TIME IN 50 YEARS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK HAZELTINE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
USIU Coach Gary Zarecky isn't deluding himself going into today's game at 
Arkansas. He just hopes that the Gulls have their pride intact when they leave 
Fayetteville. 
</P>
<P>
This was not the case when USIU played at then No. 17 Oklahoma two weeks ago. 
The Sooners ran to a 97-45 lead -- at halftime. Oklahoma went on to win, 
173-101, and took the heart out of a team that came to town with a 2-0 record. 
</P>
<P>
The Gulls have a five-game losing streak but seem to have rebounded from what 
Zarecky termed "utter devastation" at Oklahoma. USIU was competitive in losses 
to California and Loyola Marymount at home this week. 
</P>
<P>
"We have to go into Arkansas with things in perspective," Zarecky said. "We're 
just looking to get into our 11-game home stand against teams our own caliber." 
</P>
<P>
The Gulls are led by guard Kevin Bradshaw, who scored a school-record 54 points 
in a 152-137 loss to Loyola Thursday. Bradshaw is averaging 30 points and 
Demetrius Laffitte 18. 
</P>
<P>
Arkansas is led by guard Todd Day (20.5) and forward Lenzie Howell (16.5). RICK 
HAZELTINE 
</P>
