<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: DATING TEENS OFTEN MIMIC STEREOTYPES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My 16-year-old daughter, who is often a terror and always 
totally assertive at home, turned into the most passive, old-fashioned girl 
when she went on her first date. I observed this because she and her young 
boyfriend shared coffee and dessert with my husband and me before they went to 
see the film they'd selected. Both my husband and I were a bit disappointed 
because neither of us admire the passive, submissive female. What happened to 
our little feminist? -- S.B. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR S.B.: Don't be too alarmed. If your daughter has been raised to be 
independent and assertive, I doubt that she'll permanently switch roles and 
become a quiet, clinging vine. Like most youngsters on a first date, she's 
insecure and afraid of offending her partner. 
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Jerrold Lee Shapiro, an associate professor of psychology at 
the University of Santa Clara in California, youngsters often fall back on 
stereotypes on a first date. For girls, that means taking a passive role about 
initiating the date and deciding how they spend the time, and for boys, the 
script is the opposite, even though it may not feel comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
He attributes the stereotypical behavior to teen-agers' acute need to be 
accepted by peers. Youngsters are deeply concerned about how their peers see 
them and they want to be like everyone else. God forbid, they should appear to 
be different in any way. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: Recently, my wife and I inherited enough money to do a major 
remodeling job on our home. This is something we've wanted to do for years, so 
it amazes me that ever since we started we've done nothing but quarrel. Twice, 
I've walked out of the place and at one time we considered divorce. What is 
this? We were a happily married couple for 15 years. -- M.K. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR M.K.: You're not the only couple to find the whole process of remodeling 
stressful. Humans are creatures of habit and when their surroundings are in a 
state of disarray, especially if they feel they're being taken advantage of and 
they can see their money doing down the drain, stress is created that can make 
the best of marriages erupt in turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
Many architects use the parallel of pregnancy and birth to describe the anxiety 
and trauma the couples experience during this trying time. The good news is 
once it's over, couples usually begin to lick their wounds, heal and start 
enjoying the rewards of all the months of doubt. 
</P>
<P>
People invest a great deal of themselves in their houses and what is done to 
them. The choices that are made can become a kind of personal statement, where 
each spouse feels his taste is on the line. 
</P>
<P>
You can help yourselves if you try to keep the remodeling in perspective. Admit 
error and try not to blame each other when something goes wrong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
