<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: L.A. ADOPTS LENINGRAD AS ITS 16TH 'SISTER 
CITY' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council adopted Leningrad as Los Angeles' newest "Sister City" Friday, 
but in light of continued complaints of human rights abuses in that Soviet 
city, the formal resolution was amended with a call for political reform. 
</P>
<P>
Councilman Joel Wachs, who proposed the link between the two cities, said he 
hoped the new relationship would "extend the cause of peace, freedom and 
understanding between the people of the Soviet Union and the people of this 
country." 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles has 15 other such agreements with cities throughout the world, but 
the relationship with Leningrad is the first between Los Angeles and a Soviet 
city. Both cities are the second largest in their respective countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
