<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Norm Sloan, former Florida basketball coach, and his top assistant coach told a 
grand jury that former Florida star Vernon Maxwell might have turned against 
them because he thought they had revealed his drug use to reporters, a 
newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
In testimony obtained by the Palm Beach Post, Monte Towe, said: "That's 
something he has blamed, I think, on us. But we didn't have anything to do with 
it." 
</P>
<P>
Testimony by Sloan and Towe before the panel investigating drug use in the 
Gainesville area centered on Maxwell. 
</P>
<P>
Maxwell, Florida's all-time leading scorer, tested positive for cocaine use at 
the 1988 NCAA tournament. After that news broke, Maxwell's status in the NBA 
draft slipped. Projected as a possible first-round pick, he was not taken until 
late in the second round by the San Antonio Spurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
