<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LA HABRA; 
</P>
<P>
2 MORE BUSINESSES 'ADOPT' CITY SCHOOLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID F. BURKE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two La Habra businesses have become the latest to join a partnership to help 
support local schools. Leisure Manor and Landmark Bank have "adopted" the 
Walnut and El Cerritos schools, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
Awards were presented to representatives from each business by the Board of 
Trustees for the La Habra City School District earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
Walnut School Principal Pat Miller thanked the retirement home for its support. 
</P>
<P>
"They told us that they would like to host a party for us on Halloween, so we 
had a party at the Manor," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Other joint efforts have included a poster contest and visits to the school 
each week by eight volunteers from Leisure Manor. 
</P>
<P>
Among support activities provided to El Cerritos School by Landmark Bank are 
coloring books and crayons promoting Halloween safety, a supply of candy for 
monthly assemblies, balloons for student of the month awards and the 
presentation of a Christmas tree. 
</P>
<P>
"We never had (a tree) at El Cerritos. It's in the cafeteria, and we're ready 
to decorate it. It's just gorgeous," said El Cerritos Principal Myrna Close. 
</P>
<P>
Pat Rau, senior bank vice president, said plans for additional support include 
volunteer work at the school, hosting luncheons for teachers and providing 
funds for special projects. 
</P>
<P>
Board member Morrison Clements expressed delight that local businesses have 
offered to help improve the quality of education for young students. 
</P>
<P>
"There's a relationship between the kids in the school and activities in the 
community," he said. DAVID F. BURKE 
</P>
</TEXT>
